<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-253-052 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 791 803</DOCID><JOURNAL>LAN Magazine  Jan 1991 v6 n1 p142(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Telecon Library Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Erasable optical disk. (Iomega's LaserSafe) (Innovations)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dougherty, Elizabeth.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Iomega Corp. (Product introduction).andO;Ticker:    IOMG.andO;Product:   Iomega LaserSafe (Optical disk drive) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionOptical DisksDisk Drives.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Erasable Optical DiskandM;Iomega is offering an erasable, optical, mass-storage system for PCs thatuses a combination of laser and magnetic technologies to create high-densityerasable and rewritable storage.andP;  Priced at $4,999, LaserSafe, a 650MBmagneto-optical storage system, is a second-generation 5-1/4-inch opticaldisk system that operates in Unix, OS/2, and NetWare 286 environments.andP;  Thesystem is designed for environments, such as networked workgroups and largemultitasking operating environments, where high capacity, random access, andremovability are important.andM;The system's drive uses a Small Computer Systems Interface (SCSI) to connectto a variety of computers, including IBM-compatible and Macintosh PCs.andO;LaserSafe uses removable 5-1/4-inch magneto-optical ISO standard cartridges.andO;Iomega sells cartridges priced at $299 each.andM;To support the system, Iomega offers interface kits for PC bus (ISA/EISA)that cost $265, MicroChannel for $399, parallel port at $199, and Macintoshcosting $49.andM;Iomega, 1821 West 4000 South, Roy, Utah 84067, (800) 777-6654.andO;</TEXT></DOC>